<h2>Baconian Concealment Cipher Example</h2>
<p>The Baconian Cipher construction above would hardly accomplish Lord Baco=
n=E2=80=99s interest in concealing the very existence of a cipher=E2=80=99s=
 presence but consider the following text=E2=80=99s merit in using two dist=
inct features to generate a concealment device:</p>
<h3>BC-1</h3>
<p><strong><em>The =E2=80=9Cfather=E2=80=9D of the Baconian biliteral alpha=
bet type message code as we know it, was one, Lord Francis Bacon, a noted s=
cribe, philosopher, one time avid cryptologist, who strongly believed the o=
nly secret codes were those that effectively concealed the fact that any se=
cret existed.</em></strong> <em>Sixteenth Century, elite, active, English p=
olitical statesman, he used slightly=E2=80=A6</em></p>
<p>It seems an innocent and harmless enough looking piece of text but look =
at what happens to it when the author instructs the recipient of it to assi=
gn =E2=80=9Ca=E2=80=9D to words ending in a consonant and =E2=80=9Cb=E2=80=
=9D to words ending in a vowel. Convert five letter Baconian Biliteral Alph=
abet =E2=80=9Ca=E2=80=99s=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cb=E2=80=99s=E2=80=9D to pla=
intext for the concealed message.</p>
<p>See Appendix III for full message.</p>
<h2>Baconian Crib Placement</h2>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s take the time to recap the Baconian crib placement procedu=
re where no construction attempt has been made to conceal a cipher=E2=80=99=
s existence.</p>
<p><strong>BC-2. Baconian. Look for a conflict. (for) LIONEL</strong></p>
<pre>ENCRO SVFKP ERPER KREIF IWPEP EPRGB<br><br>TCMQU EGCQG CMETE YVZEL ETJ=
CO YELAV<br><br>CREHS GXCEM SOCPE XMCFE.<br><br></pre>
<p>The task before us is the assignment of letters from the Baconian Bilite=
ral Alphabet to the ciphertext to convert to a meaningful plaintext. Our fi=
rst step is to find the proper placement of our crib in the ciphertext. Fin=
d the values from the Baconian Alphabet for the crib and check all cipherte=
xt letters against these values, looking for a proper fit.</p>
<p>(See below.)</p>
<h2>Baconian Biliteral Alphabet</h2>
<table width=3D"617">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th>A=3D</th>
